<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    `com.apple.security.app-sandbox` was previously declared
    as `<false/>` here. That key is a macOS-only entitlement; on an
    iOS-only target it has no effect at runtime, but its presence in
    the entitlements plist actively misleads reviewers and SAST tools
    into thinking the app has macOS-style sandboxing controls (or
    worse, that those controls have been explicitly disabled). It has
    been removed entirely.

    iOS apps are sandboxed by default; there is no opt-in or opt-out
    entitlement for the iOS sandbox. If this codebase is ever ported to
    macOS Catalyst or AppKit, the macOS sandbox decision must be made
    deliberately at that time - it should not be inherited from a
    historical iOS plist value.

    `com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write` is similarly a
    macOS / Mac Catalyst entitlement; it is harmless on a pure iOS target
    (the Documents browser / picker on iOS does not consult it). It is
    kept here so this file remains valid if the project is ever extended
    to a Catalyst target where the picker WOULD consult it. It has no
    iOS effect today.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write</key>
    <true/>
    <!-- iCloud Documents is intentionally NOT enabled. The Android build
         deliberately routes backups through user-picked folders so
         wallets stay portable across devices without being bound to one
         iCloud account. Re-enable only if the product requirement
         changes. -->
</dict>
</plist>
